The article is a Presidential Proclamation by Barack Obama, marking the 22nd anniversary of the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA). The ADA is a historic piece of civil rights legislation that affirms the rights of Americans with disabilities. The proclamation acknowledges the progress that has been made in ensuring equality for individuals with disabilities but also highlights that there is still work to be done. The Obama Administration has taken steps to build on the legacy of the ADA, such as implementing provisions in the Affordable Care Act to protect individuals with disabilities from being denied insurance coverage. They have also established the Administration for Community Living to provide support for people with disabilities to live with dignity in their communities. The Department of Education has implemented new standards for the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act to improve outcomes for infants and toddlers with disabilities. The proclamation pays tribute to the advocates who have fought for the rights of individuals with disabilities and emphasizes the importance of equal access and opportunity for all Americans. The proclamation concludes by urging Americans to celebrate the anniversary of the ADA and the contributions of individuals with disabilities.